Why ISIS can persist
Fatal terrorist attacks in New York – Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad show the claws of the Islamic State (ISIS) have touched multiple continents in Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS maintains its strength in Syria and Iraq, the longer the days will come when its terrorist network will concoct such large-scale massacres.
However, ISIS is not particularly difficult to eradicate.
The problem is that countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not considered ISIS as their main enemy.
This point should have been changed.
ISIS has a small-scale combat force, the US predicts that it has 20,000 to 25,000 people in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 in Libya.
Compared to the number of active military personnel in Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is not worth mentioning.
In September 2014, US President Obama promised to "strike and ultimately eliminate" ISIS, but the US and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (behind the scenes), have always focused on overthrown Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
Recently, Israeli Major General Herzi Halevy (Herzi Halevy) bluntly stated (as relayed by a reporter on the scene of Halevy's speech): "Israel does not want to see the Syrian situation end with (ISIS) being defeated, superpowers exiting the region, and (Israel) facing a stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposed ISIS, but its biggest concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allowed Iran to support Israel's two quasi-military opponents — Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's priority is to overthrow Assad, not to defeat ISIS.
Under the influence of neoconservatism, for the United States, the Syrian War is a continuation of the global American hegemony plan proposed by then-Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz after the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told US General Wesley Clark:
"But we indeed learned one thing from the Gulf War, that we can use force in that region - in the Middle East - while the Soviets will not stop us."
"We have about 5 to 10 years to clean up the old Soviet regime - Syria, Iran, Iraq - before the next superpower challenges us."
"The US wars in the Middle East - Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. - have been to make the Soviets and then the Russians withdraw from the competition, and for the US to monopolize power."
"These 'efforts' have been disastrous."
"For Saudi Arabia, and for Israel, the main goal is to overthrow Assad to weaken Iran."
Syria is a part of a massive proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which is being played out in Syria, Yemen and other arenas, as well as on the frontlines in Bahrain and other countries in the region that have sectarian divisions (including Saudi Arabia itself).
For Turkey, toppling Assad would strengthen its regional status.
But Turkey is currently facing three opponents on its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
Until now, ISIS is not as important to Turkey as Assad and the Kurds.
But terrorist attacks in Turkey orchestrated by ISIS may change this situation.
Russia and Iran are also pursuing their own regional interests, through proxy wars and supporting quasi-military actions.
However, both countries have stated to be ready to cooperate with the US to strike ISIS, and they can also cooperate in solving other issues.
So far, the US has been indifferent, because its focus is on toppling Assad.
US diplomacy has condemned Russian President Putin for shielding Assad, while Russia has condemned the US for trying to overthrow Assad.
These complaints seem to be mutually exclusive, but they are not.
US and its allies' attempt to overthrow Assad violated the United Nations Charter, while Russia's support for Assad conforms to the Charter's stipulation on Syria's right to self-defense.
Indeed, Assad is a tyrant, but the United Nations Charter has not granted any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
The persistence of ISIS highlights three strategic flaws and a fatal tactical flaw in US diplomacy.
Firstly, neoconservatism's call for US dominance through regime change is not only a bloody and ignorant thought; it is also an overambitious classic imperialism.
Wherever the US has attempted this, it has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Secondly, the CIA has long armed and trained Sunni extremist groups with funding from Saudi Arabia.
Conversely, these extremist groups have spawned ISIS, which is a direct (or perhaps unexpected) consequence of CIA and its Saudi allies' policy.
Thirdly, the US viewing Iran and Russia as America's irreconcilable enemies to a great extent is a self-fulfilling prophecy.
It is possible to remake relationships with the two countries.
Fourthly, at the tactical level, the US attempt to win the war against Assad and ISIS has already failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni extremists including ISIS and the al-Nusra Front fill the vacuum.
If the US, Russia, Saudi Arabia and Iran provided air cover and logistical support, Assad and his Iraqi allies could defeat ISIS.
Surely, Assad would continue to rule; surely, Russia would continue to be Syria's ally; surely, Iran would gain influence in the region.
Terrorist attacks would undoubtedly continue, perhaps for a period of time, under the ISIS banner; but the organization would be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
This outcome not only can eradicate ISIS on the vast land of the Middle East, but also lay a foundation for more comprehensive relaxation of the regional tension.
The US and Russia can jointly start to reverse the recent new Cold War by expelling the holy war terrorism.
(The NATO promise not to let Ukraine join the alliance or not to upgrade the ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe could also be beneficial.)
There are other benefits.
Adopting a collaborative approach to strike at ISIS would give Saudi Arabia and Turkey a reason and an opportunity to find new temporary measures to approach Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened by allowing Iran to build cooperative economic and geopolitical relations with the West, which in turn increases the chances for a gradual reconciliation between Israel and the Palestinians.
The rise of ISIS is a manifestation of the current strategic shortcomings of the West, particularly the United States.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The question is whether the US will carry out the strategic reassessment needed to achieve this goal.
